1) Q: Explain Angular architecture / complete project flow?

Answer:
In Angular, the application works using Components, Services, Modules, Routing, and APIs.

Angular Architecture:- combination of multiple building blocks
➡️component - basic building block of angular UI
➡️module - group of components and service
➡️service - used for business logic and api calls
➡️template - used for where write html code.
➡️Directive - control dom Behavior(show hide)
➡️Routing - navigation between pages


Yes, when Angular application starts, browser first loads index.html. 
After that, Angular executes main.ts file, which bootstraps the application by loading AppModule.
AppModule then loads the root component (AppComponent), and Angular renders it inside app-root.
From there, routing and other components start loading.

1. Browser Open
   → User opens the Angular app URL.
   → Browser starts loading the application.

2. index.html (It provides an empty placeholder (`<app-root>`) for Angular.)
       ↓
3. main.ts (This is the entry point of the Angular app, It starts Angular and loads `AppModule`.)
       ↓
4. AppModule (app.module.ts) (This is the main configuration file of the app., It decides which component should load first.)
In bootstrap: [AppComponent]
       ↓
5. AppComponent (It connects `<app-root>` with actual Angular content)
Yani browser ke empty <app-root> ke andar AppComponent inject hoga.
       ↓
6. app.component.html (This renders the first UI of the application.)
       ↓
7. Routing (It loads components based on the current URL)
       ↓
8. Required Component
   (home/dashboard.component.ts)
   → The logic of that page runs here.
   → API calls, functions, and data handling happen here.

The complete flow in our project is:

User performs an action like opening a page or clicking a button.
The component handles UI and calls a service.
The service makes API calls using HttpClient.
The API returns data as an Observable.
In the component, we use subscribe() to get the response.
After receiving data, we store it in variables and bind it to HTML using interpolation, property binding, or directives.
Angular change detection automatically updates the UI.

Flow:

User Action
   ↓
Component
   ↓
Service
   ↓
API Call
   ↓
Observable
   ↓
subscribe()
   ↓
Data Binding
   ↓
UI Updated

For large applications, we use reusable components, shared modules, and lazy loading to improve performance.

